So Pitfall Avoidance, first part is over.

241
00:13:09,972 --> 00:13:11,454
We can create memorable behavior.

242
00:13:11,754 --> 00:13:13,216
We know that we need some kind of emotion.

243
00:13:13,817 --> 00:13:15,460
And we know that it has something to do with

244
00:13:16,301 --> 00:13:18,624
strengthening the emotion after the effect.

245
00:13:19,465 --> 00:13:21,548
The next chapter will be specifically about body AI.

246
00:13:22,389 --> 00:13:26,734
And I put this in here because buddy AI, a lot of the things that I just said apply to

247
00:13:26,774 --> 00:13:32,460
buddy AI, but buddy AI has very different challenges than your average enemy or friendly

248
00:13:32,580 --> 00:13:32,700
AI.

249
00:13:33,861 --> 00:13:38,145
The chapter is called the buddy AI is not your friend, or how to design the buddy AI

250
00:13:38,185 --> 00:13:39,066
around the needs of the game.

251
00:13:41,372 --> 00:13:43,412
By buddy I mean a lot of different things here.

252
00:13:45,093 --> 00:13:50,174
I mean all kinds of friendly AIs that play with the player and are part of the game.

253
00:13:50,234 --> 00:13:54,616
Some people call it companions, some people call it team AI, all of those, all of these

254
00:13:54,656 --> 00:13:55,336
guys are meant.

255
00:13:55,836 --> 00:13:56,076
Right?

256
00:13:56,136 --> 00:14:00,237
I mean something like Elizabeth, I mean something like the RoboDoc I just introduced, I mean

257
00:14:00,397 --> 00:14:01,978
teammates and squadmates, all of them.

258
00:14:03,119 --> 00:14:04,860
So the scenario is this.

259
00:14:05,320 --> 00:14:07,100
You're working on Buddy AI.

260
00:14:07,120 --> 00:14:09,741
And you know Buddy AI has special needs.

261
00:14:09,881 --> 00:14:11,602
It's really hard to get people to agree

262
00:14:11,642 --> 00:14:12,722
on what is good Buddy AI.

263
00:14:13,402 --> 00:14:15,363
And you might think, I want to model the AI

264
00:14:15,523 --> 00:14:16,563
after what the player wants.

265
00:14:17,444 --> 00:14:18,524
And it sounds like a good idea.

266
00:14:18,644 --> 00:14:20,825
The pitfall, I will say right ahead,

267
00:14:21,045 --> 00:14:21,885
yes, pitfall of the game,

268
00:14:23,006 --> 00:14:24,966
is to build up player entitlement.

269
00:14:25,686 --> 00:14:26,827
And to explain what I mean by that,

270
00:14:26,867 --> 00:14:28,127
I will first give you some examples,

271
00:14:28,147 --> 00:14:28,947
then spell it out for you.

272
00:14:30,088 --> 00:14:31,528
All right, so first example.

273
00:14:32,388 --> 00:14:33,408
the buddy AI can revive you.

274
00:14:33,608 --> 00:14:34,908
You are working on some team shooter,

275
00:14:35,929 --> 00:14:36,929
and the player goes down,

276
00:14:36,969 --> 00:14:39,250
and there's two or three AI teammates,

277
00:14:39,490 --> 00:14:40,570
and they can come and revive you.

278
00:14:41,390 --> 00:14:41,970
Why wouldn't they?

279
00:14:42,771 --> 00:14:43,911
But you have no economy,

280
00:14:43,931 --> 00:14:45,871
you have no health packs,

281
00:14:45,891 --> 00:14:48,112
or instant death, or timeout.

282
00:14:48,672 --> 00:14:50,112
And then you get into a real problem,

283
00:14:50,132 --> 00:14:52,233
because technically you can never die.

284
00:14:52,473 --> 00:14:54,154
The AI can always come and revive you, right?

285
00:14:54,974 --> 00:14:57,874
And even if the AI fails for obvious reasons,

286
00:14:57,915 --> 00:14:58,735
like getting shot,

287
00:14:59,175 --> 00:15:00,555
the player will not accept that.

288
00:15:01,175 --> 00:15:04,718
I had that problem actually in Fuse, where we had exactly this issue, where it went so

289
00:15:04,758 --> 00:15:09,762
far as the AI would come over, would bend down to try to revive you, get shot in the

290
00:15:09,782 --> 00:15:12,063
head, and the player would still say the AI failed.

291
00:15:12,223 --> 00:15:12,804
The AI sucks.

292
00:15:14,405 --> 00:15:15,025
Another example.

293
00:15:15,786 --> 00:15:21,130
Buddy AI supports combat, fighting with you is part of the setups, and there is no tracking

294
00:15:21,150 --> 00:15:21,951
of the player progress.

295
00:15:22,952 --> 00:15:27,854
Nothing that checks how many people the player shot or whether he pushed forward the combat.

296
00:15:28,414 --> 00:15:33,535
And then you get YouTube videos of Call of Duty Black Ops that play themselves and the

297
00:15:33,735 --> 00:15:34,435
player just watches.

298
00:15:34,936 --> 00:15:38,176
And you can argue that's what this game is supposed to do.

299
00:15:38,397 --> 00:15:41,677
It's not about challenge, it's about feeling in the middle, you don't actually have to

300
00:15:41,737 --> 00:15:41,998
play.

301
00:15:42,798 --> 00:15:47,179
But at the very least you're not matching the player expectation here, which is I'm

302
00:15:47,199 --> 00:15:49,120
the hero, I'm the most important person in this game.

303
00:15:50,400 --> 00:15:52,521
The third example, this is really contentious.

304
00:15:53,001 --> 00:15:57,122
Every time I talk about this, there is 50-50 people who agree and completely disagree with

305
00:15:57,142 --> 00:15:57,282
this.

306
00:15:57,982 --> 00:15:59,262
The buddy AI gives you ammunition.

307
00:16:00,643 --> 00:16:02,323
There is no rules on how much.

308
00:16:02,523 --> 00:16:06,004
You just press a button, you get ammunition, and you get really used to that.

309
00:16:06,384 --> 00:16:10,025
And then if it's missing, you get really annoyed, or at least I get really annoyed.

310
00:16:10,485 --> 00:16:12,265
That is my one problem with Elizabeth.

311
00:16:12,625 --> 00:16:17,327
She is amazing, and I will talk about how amazing she is later, but this is my one issue.

312
00:16:17,387 --> 00:16:19,867
I get annoyed with her when she wasn't there or when she wasn't working.

313
00:16:21,228 --> 00:16:27,311
And the fact that half the people agree and half the people don't agree with this just proves my point that you never know what people expect.

314
00:16:28,552 --> 00:16:37,457
So player entitlement is about spoiling the player. It's about giving the player what he wants until he either doesn't care anymore or he's really upset when it's missing.

315
00:16:38,477 --> 00:16:44,941
And it's also about different expectations. Everybody wants something else from Buddy AI and you can't really guess what it's going to be.

316
00:16:45,281 --> 00:16:49,663
For some people this is sushi and it's amazing and for other people it's raw fish and they don't want it.

317
00:16:51,297 --> 00:16:53,780
So, you might want to go about it differently.

318
00:16:54,281 --> 00:16:54,841
At least I do.

319
00:16:55,482 --> 00:16:59,607
I'm trying to, when I go for body height these days, I'm trying to model it around the needs

320
00:16:59,647 --> 00:17:00,067
of the game.

321
00:17:00,448 --> 00:17:01,689
And that sounds very obvious, right?

322
00:17:01,729 --> 00:17:04,012
It sounds like, oh sure, we all try to make the game better.

323
00:17:05,253 --> 00:17:05,774
That's the goal.

324
00:17:06,715 --> 00:17:09,698
But what does it mean, and what is really helping the game?

325
00:17:11,031 --> 00:17:13,975
For me, there's three categories. These are my categories.

326
00:17:14,456 --> 00:17:19,364
You might agree, you might have different names, you might mix and match them, which sometimes works and sometimes doesn't.

327
00:17:19,904 --> 00:17:21,267
But these are my three categories.

328
00:17:21,767 --> 00:17:23,771
The teacher, the VIP and the soldier.

329
00:17:25,137 --> 00:17:27,518
The teacher explains the world, right?

330
00:17:27,798 --> 00:17:31,219
He is there to give you the background, the plot, the story,

331
00:17:31,819 --> 00:17:32,880
explains to you why you're there.

332
00:17:33,700 --> 00:17:37,702
The teacher is leading the way, showing you around,

333
00:17:37,822 --> 00:17:39,782
leading you by the hand, showing you a door,

334
00:17:40,242 --> 00:17:41,303
showing you a loot crate.

335
00:17:41,583 --> 00:17:44,284
Maybe it's a dog that finds some equipment

336
00:17:44,304 --> 00:17:44,924
for you in the world.

337
00:17:45,424 --> 00:17:47,305
But the teacher does not fight normally.

338
00:17:47,505 --> 00:17:49,966
The teacher is an academic, doesn't care about combat.

339
00:17:50,766 --> 00:17:55,389
And that's really where Elisabeth is good. That is why I like her. Not the other thing, not the giving me gifts.

340
00:17:56,069 --> 00:17:57,410
That is where she's the best at, I think.

341
00:17:58,731 --> 00:18:00,612
The second category is the VIP.

342
00:18:01,672 --> 00:18:04,174
VIP is the purpose of the game, the purpose of the mission.

343
00:18:04,854 --> 00:18:06,555
It's really why you're there and why you're playing this.

344
00:18:06,975 --> 00:18:08,616
The VIP cannot die.

345
00:18:09,116 --> 00:18:14,740
Meaning, either the VIP is immortal, or if the VIP dies, you're lost.

346
00:18:16,640 --> 00:18:22,566
And that's usually where you find codependence, where like you save the VIP and eventually the VIP will do something for you.

347
00:18:23,627 --> 00:18:26,349
My favorite example for this is Ellie from The Last of Us.

348
00:18:27,611 --> 00:18:33,656
Without spoiling anything, she is the reason you make you play this game and more important than anything else.

349
00:18:35,151 --> 00:18:36,211
The last category is the soldier.

350
00:18:36,732 --> 00:18:41,633
The soldier is everybody who fights, everybody who supports combat, either just helping the

351
00:18:41,673 --> 00:18:45,254
player or just being fluff, being background, making the combat larger.

352
00:18:46,775 --> 00:18:51,776
And most importantly, and that's really important for me, the soldier can die and it shouldn't

353
00:18:51,816 --> 00:18:52,056
matter.

354
00:18:52,597 --> 00:18:57,778
Like, if the AI does something wrong, if the AI goes down, it shouldn't at all influence

355
00:18:57,798 --> 00:18:58,098
your game.

356
00:18:59,099 --> 00:19:01,200
Any team shooter has soldiers like this, right?

357
00:19:01,240 --> 00:19:02,621
Like Halo or Call of Duty.

358
00:19:03,001 --> 00:19:04,862
Things in the background that don't really matter for the player.

359
00:19:05,623 --> 00:19:07,904
So you can mix and match those.

360
00:19:08,404 --> 00:19:12,386
But if you, for example, create a VIP AI that is also a soldier,

361
00:19:12,767 --> 00:19:17,690
you basically just create an escort mission where it depends on the AI whether your game progresses or not.

362
00:19:20,160 --> 00:19:24,023
So, what happens if you don't work for the player's needs, right?

363
00:19:24,324 --> 00:19:25,725
Why should the player care about all this?

364
00:19:26,045 --> 00:19:27,827
Well, for all the reasons I explained before.

365
00:19:28,227 --> 00:19:30,389
The player should care for an emotional connection.

366
00:19:30,429 --> 00:19:31,930
He should care because he likes the AI.

367
00:19:32,230 --> 00:19:34,412
He should care for story and character reasons.

368
00:19:34,953 --> 00:19:38,336
And lastly, he should care because you play together with the AI.

369
00:19:38,536 --> 00:19:41,539
The AI saves you, you save her, works together.

370
00:19:43,260 --> 00:19:44,461
Alright, to recap this part.

371
00:19:45,419 --> 00:19:49,941
Prevent player entitlement. Be very careful about your assumptions about what the player wants

372
00:19:50,561 --> 00:19:55,642
and that you think you know what actually makes the player happy, because everybody has a different expectation here.

373
00:19:56,122 --> 00:20:00,124
Design around the needs of the game. If you can, think really hard about what your game is missing.

374
00:20:00,564 --> 00:20:03,945
Is it missing some story explanation? Is it missing someone who leads it by the hand?

375
00:20:04,305 --> 00:20:07,706
Is it missing a purpose? Like, why am I doing all this? Why am I fighting?

376
00:20:08,706 --> 00:20:09,307
Fill that need.

377
00:20:10,287 --> 00:20:12,608
And finally, motivate through story and emotion.

378
00:20:13,685 --> 00:20:16,006
Think about how you can get an emotional connection

379
00:20:16,566 --> 00:20:17,386
and motivate through that.

380
00:20:18,367 --> 00:20:19,047
Pitfall avoided.

381
00:20:20,007 --> 00:20:21,148
We know we need some emotion.

382
00:20:22,148 --> 00:20:24,449
We know that the buddy AI can spoil the player

383
00:20:24,489 --> 00:20:25,550
and we have to be careful about it.

384
00:20:26,010 --> 00:20:27,471
We can make good friendly AI,

385
00:20:27,871 --> 00:20:30,052
but we haven't talked at all about enemy AI.

386
00:20:30,452 --> 00:20:32,653
So the last chapter is solely about enemy AI

387
00:20:32,673 --> 00:20:33,413
and it's wrapping it up.

388
00:20:34,454 --> 00:20:35,494
The last chapter is called

389
00:20:36,014 --> 00:20:37,895
Escalation is the Mother of All Challenge.

390
00:20:39,076 --> 00:20:41,136
Or, Why Repetition is Better Than Its Reputation.

391
00:20:43,347 --> 00:20:49,950
So, to repeat myself, we're talking about memorable experiences, right?

392
00:20:49,970 --> 00:20:53,092
We're talking about how to make the game memorable for the player.

393
00:20:53,852 --> 00:20:56,173
And you might wonder, what does it have to do with challenge?

394
00:20:57,492 --> 00:21:01,115
Well, you remember the study I was talking about before,

395
00:21:02,256 --> 00:21:05,959
of Professor McGaw, who was taking group A and group B,

396
00:21:06,359 --> 00:21:09,802
and group A was looking at kitchen sink items,

397
00:21:10,022 --> 00:21:14,005
and group B was looking at emotional arousing objects?

398
00:21:15,326 --> 00:21:17,688
Well, he did some more work on this,

399
00:21:18,269 --> 00:21:20,010
and one of the sentences you might remember is,

400
00:21:20,070 --> 00:21:21,731
stress hormones can strengthen memory.

401
00:21:23,047 --> 00:21:25,868
So what he did there is the so-called ice water trial.

402
00:21:25,968 --> 00:21:28,249
He basically took the two groups,

403
00:21:28,529 --> 00:21:29,309
and he split them up again.

404
00:21:29,329 --> 00:21:35,411
And one half of them would just get a bucket of warm water

405
00:21:36,511 --> 00:21:38,212
and were asked to hold their hand in it.

406
00:21:38,232 --> 00:21:41,153
And the other one was given a bucket of ice water

407
00:21:41,673 --> 00:21:43,854
and asked to hold their hand in the ice water

408
00:21:44,274 --> 00:21:45,254
until it really hurt,

409
00:21:46,234 --> 00:21:48,355
until they couldn't hold it anymore in there.

410
00:21:49,315 --> 00:21:50,536
Basically he was torturing them, right?

411
00:21:52,750 --> 00:21:53,832
So the result was this.

412
00:21:54,633 --> 00:22:00,422
As soon as you mixed emotion with stress, with pain, your memory would jump up.

413
00:22:02,085 --> 00:22:04,388
50 plus percent better recollection of what just happened.

414
00:22:05,476 --> 00:22:11,019
And the interesting thing to note here too in this chart is on the right side are the neutral items, on the left side the arousing items.

415
00:22:11,520 --> 00:22:18,084
So on the right side you can actually see that stress, when induced on the neutral items, reduced your memory.

416
00:22:18,384 --> 00:22:24,368
It really only works together when you mix the two, stress and emotional interesting items.

417
00:22:25,347 --> 00:22:26,589
that makes memory strong.

418
00:22:27,250 --> 00:22:30,174
So, to talk about challenge here,

419
00:22:31,216 --> 00:22:33,359
let's say the goal is we have some combat set up

420
00:22:33,640 --> 00:22:36,865
and you're asked to make it harder or make it longer,

421
00:22:36,905 --> 00:22:39,569
it's too short, it's too easy, fix that.

422
00:22:40,534 --> 00:22:45,776
And your approach might be to repeat an existing behavior, an existing mechanic, three, four,

423
00:22:45,836 --> 00:22:46,356
five times.

424
00:22:47,116 --> 00:22:48,117
And it totally makes sense.

425
00:22:48,217 --> 00:22:49,157
That is the right approach.

426
00:22:50,277 --> 00:22:52,338
Because repetition is really good for your game.

427
00:22:53,238 --> 00:22:58,020
Here's a quote from Ziggy Ziggler, the father of all motivational speakers.

428
00:22:59,760 --> 00:23:04,362
Repetition is the mother of learning, the father of action, which makes it the architect

429
00:23:04,422 --> 00:23:05,122
of accomplishment.

430
00:23:05,962 --> 00:23:07,383
And this really speaks for action games.

431
00:23:07,403 --> 00:23:08,263
That's what we do, right?

432
00:23:08,343 --> 00:23:09,324
That's what it's all about.

433
00:23:09,664 --> 00:23:11,185
We want the player to learn.

434
00:23:11,545 --> 00:23:16,589
We want the player to repeat the behavior, get better at it, get skill over time, and

435
00:23:16,609 --> 00:23:19,931
then overcome the game, beat the game, feel accomplished.

436
00:23:20,391 --> 00:23:24,954
And also for developers, this is really important because we can reuse our work.

437
00:23:25,214 --> 00:23:30,238
We can have the player fight the same AI 50 times instead of making 50 different AIs.

438
00:23:31,038 --> 00:23:31,959
So repetition is good.

439
00:23:33,768 --> 00:23:37,031
The problem is, you can very quickly cheapen the experience for the player.

440
00:23:37,091 --> 00:23:39,874
If you do the same thing over and over, the player will get bored, right?

441
00:23:40,434 --> 00:23:43,096
He will feel too skillful for what you throw at him.

442
00:23:44,217 --> 00:23:46,319
He will think that you didn't come up with anything better.

443
00:23:47,360 --> 00:23:52,044
So the approach that people take oftentimes, that I took in the past, was to say, okay,

444
00:23:52,184 --> 00:23:53,605
we add some weak spots.

445
00:23:53,705 --> 00:23:54,486
We add some turrets.

446
00:23:54,526 --> 00:23:58,629
You have a giant monster and it has five turrets on it, and you have to first destroy the turrets.

447
00:23:58,709 --> 00:23:59,770
And the turrets shoot little rockets.

448
00:24:00,470 --> 00:24:01,531
That is a really bad idea.

449
00:24:03,007 --> 00:24:03,588
And here's why.

450
00:24:04,249 --> 00:24:06,272
Destroying weak spots, especially if it's weapons,

451
00:24:06,792 --> 00:24:08,815
is kind of like cutting off the heads of a hydra.

452
00:24:09,971 --> 00:24:14,895
Hydra is obviously the giant serpent with seven or ten heads of the old Greek mythology

453
00:24:15,376 --> 00:24:18,338
and it was fighting all the Greek heroes and you would cut off some heads and you would

454
00:24:18,358 --> 00:24:23,582
cut off some more heads and cut off some more and now the combat is boring and sucks because

455
00:24:23,642 --> 00:24:26,244
there is no heads left and it's just like a snake, right?

456
00:24:27,105 --> 00:24:28,626
And the Greeks knew that, they were smart in that.

457
00:24:29,126 --> 00:24:31,608
They knew they needed a real challenge for their heroes.

458
00:24:31,929 --> 00:24:32,689
So they said no, no, no.

459
00:24:33,577 --> 00:24:35,057
the heads grow back, or even better,

460
00:24:35,437 --> 00:24:37,518
every time you cut off a head, there's two heads coming out.

461
00:24:38,179 --> 00:24:39,499
And that's really how you get challenge.

462
00:24:39,859 --> 00:24:41,480
You really make the player think about it,

463
00:24:41,520 --> 00:24:43,901
and if you do something wrong, it's going to get harder.

464
00:24:45,442 --> 00:24:48,203
So instead of thinking about just adding weak spots

465
00:24:48,263 --> 00:24:49,644
or just doing the same thing over and over,

466
00:24:50,284 --> 00:24:52,885
add heads, make it harder every time

467
00:24:52,905 --> 00:24:54,066
you progress through the combat.

468
00:24:54,506 --> 00:24:57,407
Make it harder with each step, and increase the challenge.

469
00:24:57,467 --> 00:24:59,208
Because the player learned something, the player got better,

470
00:24:59,688 --> 00:25:01,069
so your challenge has to become greater.

471
00:25:02,143 --> 00:25:04,985
Alright, so think of this as escalating the combat.

472
00:25:05,445 --> 00:25:08,147
Like think of your enemy like a wounded animal.

473
00:25:08,827 --> 00:25:14,712
Think of it like what would happen if the enemy was scared, it was in a corner, it was

474
00:25:15,212 --> 00:25:16,753
more defensive or more aggressive.

475
00:25:17,413 --> 00:25:22,197
Add attacks, don't show everything at the beginning, actually hold it back and during

476
00:25:22,237 --> 00:25:25,039
the progress of the battle bring out your extra stuff.

477
00:25:26,625 --> 00:25:30,727
Scale combat intensity. This is really easy for programmers. Just put in some sliders.

478
00:25:31,227 --> 00:25:36,910
Put in a slider of how much damage output you do per second, or how fast you react to

479
00:25:36,930 --> 00:25:42,072
the player, or how quickly you mix things up. And as the combat progresses, you just

